  "prompt": "What does the Chinese word \u300c\u6c14\u8d28\u300dmean?",
  "response": "The Chinese word \u300c\u6c14\u8d28\u300d(q\u00ec zh\u00ed) can be translated in several ways, depending on the context:\n\n1. Temperament: It refers to a person's innate character, personality, or disposition.\n\n2. Demeanor: The way a person carries themselves, their bearing, or personal style.\n\n3. Aura: The distinctive atmosphere or quality that surrounds a person.\n\n4. Charisma: A compelling attractiveness or charm that inspires devotion in others.\n\n5. Innate qualities: The inherent characteristics that define a person's essence or nature.\n\nIn general, \u300c\u6c14\u8d28\u300ddescribes the external manifestation of a person's internal qualities, including their personality, style, and overall impression they give to others. It's often used to describe someone's refined or elegant manner, or their unique personal charm.\n\nFor example:\n- \u5979\u6709\u5f88\u9ad8\u7684\u6c14\u8d28 (T\u0101 y\u01d2u h\u011bn g\u0101o de q\u00eczh\u00ed) - She has a very refined demeanor\n- \u4ed6\u7684\u6c14\u8d28\u5f88\u4f18\u96c5 (T\u0101 de q\u00eczh\u00ed h\u011bn y\u014duy\u01ce) - His temperament is very elegant",
